Adults are common in the lowlands (7 to 356 m a.s.l.) and appear to be generalists in a variety of rainforest biotopes including terra firme and 
varzea
. In these forests, they are commonly found in big trees with vines and epiphytes, in suspended dry leaves, in dry 

Sheelea

sp. and 

Astrocaryum chambira

Burret palm frond skirts. Individuals can be found from January to December, in both the rainy and dry seasons. Member of this species have been recorded from the canopy of the following tree species using insecticidal fogging techniques: 

Chrysophyllum argenteum

cf.; 

